Parkinson's is a slowly progressing brain disease extensively researched in the U.S., as it affects 1.5 million Americans, sufferers including Muhammad Ali, Janet Reno, and Michael Fox.
Symptoms include difficulty in walking and pronouncing words, tremors, and stiffness.
Supporters of embryonic stem cell research are hopeful it will lead to the amelioration of Parkinson's.
The National Institute on Aging is studying a gene which when mutated causes Parkinson's.
University of Pittsburgh researchers are studying exercise as a Parkinson's preventer, findings in rats showing that heightened activity led to reduced brain degeneration.
